        "solution": "Assume there are finitely many such primes p_1, ..., p_k. Let N = (2p_1...p_k)^2 + 1. Let q be a prime divisor of N. Then (2p_1...p_k)^2 ≡ −1 (mod q). This implies −1 is a quadratic residue modulo q, so the Legendre symbol (-1/q) = 1. By Euler's criterion, this requires q ≡ 1 (mod 4). Since q divides N, q is distinct from any p_i (as N ≡ 1 mod p_i). Thus, q is a new prime of the form 4k+1, contradicting finiteness."
