        "problem": "Show that any graph with n vertices and more than ⌊n²/4⌋ edges contains a triangle.",
        "solution": "This is Mantel's Theorem. A bipartite graph with partition sizes k and n-k has k(n-k) edges, maximized when k = ⌊n/2⌋, giving ⌊n²/4⌋ edges. If a graph has more edges than this maximum for bipartite graphs, it cannot be bipartite. However, non-bipartite does not guarantee a triangle (e.g. C5). The rigorous proof (Turán's) shows that the unique triangle-free graph with maximum edges is the complete bipartite graph K_{⌊n/2⌋, ⌈n/2⌉}. Any additional edge must connect two vertices in the same partition, forming a triangle with a vertex in the other partition."
